{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17517832","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17517832"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:57:20+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:57:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12839"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12839","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12839"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.08,0.06,0.05,0.71]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5282"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"42147"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5282","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5282"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12839"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"27150"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1445"},{"type":"tags","id":"3675"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4984"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8991"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10562"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44384"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"42147","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/42147"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old woman presents with a three day history of high grade fever, headache, retro-orbital pain and generalised body aches. She is normally in good health and has recently returned from a diving holiday in Thailand.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination she has an obvious blanchable maculopapular rash on her arms and legs. Her blood pressure is 92/60 mmHg, pulse 100/min, temperature 40\u00b0C and respiratory rate 15/minute. The rest of the physical examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESome basic laboratory investigations are performed and show a haemoglobin of 125 g/L (115\u2013165\u003Cstrong\u003E), \u003C/strong\u003Ehaematocrit 45% (36%-44), WBC 3.0 x 10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L (4.0-11.0) and platelets 40x 10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L (150-400). Her biochemistry results are within normal limits.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Malaria","Chikungunya","Zika virus","Yellow fever","Dengue fever"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe given scenario of a young woman with high grade fever, arthralgia, retro orbital pain, leucopaenia, thrombocytopenia and raised haematocrit is consistent with dengue fever.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDengue fever is an arthropod-borne viral disease transmitted by mosquitoes, particularly Aedes aegypti. It is usually distributed throughout the tropical  and sub-tropical regions, especially thoughout Asia. It presents with the array of symptoms such as high grade fever, myalgia, headache arthralgia (often referred to as break bone fever), maculopapular rash, and in severe cases, ascites, pleural effusion and haemorrhage due to thrombocytopenia and shock (dengue haemorrhagic fever).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMalaria\u003C/strong\u003E is a close differential of dengue. It usually presents with a high grade \u003Cstrong\u003Eperiodic\u003C/strong\u003E fever usually occurring after 48-72 hours interval, depending upon the species involved. The laboratory values would show an haemolytic anaemia (decreased haemoglobin, increased bilirubin) unlike that described in this scenario. Malaria is usually found in the tropical regions of Africa and not found in the major tourist resorts in Thailand.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChikungunya \u003C/strong\u003Eis another important close differential and differs from dengue in the severity of joint pain and rashes. This infection is spread via the same Aedes aegypti mosquito that is responsible for the spread of dengue. In chikungunya, the patient presents with severe persistent debilitating bilateral polyarthralgia\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003Eand a rash which involves face, trunk and limbs, unlike in dengue which affects face and limbs only.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EZika virus \u003C/strong\u003Eusually\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003Epresents asymptomatic but can present with low grade, short lived fever, associated with pruritic maculopapular rash, headache, non-purulent conjunctivitis, and other flu-like symptoms such as malaise, myalgia and arthralgia. Zika virus is also transmitted by the Aedes aegypti mosquito. Although Zika virus is found in Thailand and can cause leukopenia and thrombocytopenia, the presence of a high-grade fever in this scenario makes dengue a more likely answer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EYellow fever\u003C/strong\u003E is also transmitted by the\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003EAedes aegypti mosquito. Yellow fever usually presents with fever, headache, myalgia, profound jaundice, examination may reveal fever-pulse dissociation (unusual pairing of fever with bradycardia), facial flushing and conjunctival injection. which is not consistent with the scenario. Yellow fever is not found in Thailand. This disease is only found in sub-Saharan Africa and parts of Central and South America.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["In a patient with recent travel to tropics, who presents with fever, it is important to rule out malaria, dengue, yellow fever, chikungunya, which are associated with severe complications if not treated on time.","Dengue is a vector-borne disease which is self limiting but needs supportive treatment. It usually starts with high grade fever, arthralgia, rash and proceed to cause third spacing leading to ascites, pleural effusion and hypotension. it also reduces platelets count significantly leading to mild bleeding to severe haemorrhage."],"references":["Schaefer TJ, Panda PK, Wolford RW. Dengue Fever. [Updated 2022 Nov 14]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2023 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK430732/","Wolford RW, Schaefer TJ. Zika Virus. [Updated 2023 Aug 7]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2023 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK430981/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"27150"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12839"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"27150","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/27150"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-01-31T16:40:21+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-01-31T16:40:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5282"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"42147"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"d